{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The wait time between retries doubles with each consecutive failure, up to a configured maximum.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Failure boundary is the backoff calculation/state progression itself (pure logic). No module boundary, I/O, or scheduler behavior is required to catch an incorrect doubling/cap rule.","test_description":"Test a backoff policy function/object directly with consecutive failure counts (e.g., 1..N) and assert delays follow 2^k growth and clamp at maxDelay.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.82,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The retry logic correctly identifies a rate-limit response and computes the appropriate wait time before the next attempt.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failures typically occur at the boundary between HTTP response translation and retry policy (status/header parsing + backoff decision). Unit tests on either side can miss contract mismatches.","test_description":"Wire retry orchestrator with the real response-classification module and backoff policy; feed representative 429/limit responses (including headers like retry-after) and assert the computed next-attempt delay is correct.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"After the wait, the client actually resends the original request and returns the successful result to the caller transparently.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior depends on orchestrating retry timer + request executor + result propagation. A unit test of one function would not prove end-to-end resend transparency.","test_description":"Use fake clock + stub transport in a wired client: first response is rate-limited, second succeeds. Advance time by